  "why": "The paper's method, LipFuzzer, is explicitly designed to generate plausible and natural inputs. Semantic consistency, as defined by the metric (preserving the meaning of the seed), is not applicable because the fuzzer's specific goal is to induce semantic misinterpretation in the voice assistant's NLU component. The oracle does not assume semantic equivalence but rather checks if an incorrect intent is triggered. Naturalness, however, is a core design principle and is enforced throughout the fuzzing process. The fuzzer is guided by 'LAPSUS Models,' which are Bayesian Networks trained on linguistic knowledge and real user data to model the probability of common, real-world spoken errors. This approach restricts the search space to a learned plausible distribution of inputs. Furthermore, the fuzzer generates mutations directly from the original seed template rather than iteratively mutating previous outputs, as stated in the evaluation section. This design directly prevents the problem of cumulative distortion (drift) and ensures that all generated inputs are constrained by the global model of what constitutes a realistic speech error.",
